{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Wee7vTDfo2t5i7TENpebSS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. Stage 01 preconditions created:\n   - `es-cluster` StatefulSet with ES 7.17.9\n   - `es-cluster` headless service (for transport/discovery on 9300)\n   - `es-http` service (pointing to `app: es-cluster` pods on 9200)\n   - `curl-test` pod\n\n2. The `es-http` service selector is `app: es-cluster`\n\n3. My task in stage 02 is to deploy ES 8.11.1 with HTTPS\n\nThe prompt says TLS secrets exist but they don't. I need to create them.\nI'm realizing the `es-http` service already targets `app: es-cluster`, so I can't just add the new ES 8.11.1 pods with the same label—that would split traffic between both versions. I need to either replace the old StatefulSet entirely or use a different label and update the service selector to point to the new deployment. I need to reconsider the headless service setup. The existing `es-cluster` headless service only exposes port 9300 for transport/discovery, which is actually what I need for ES 8.11.1 cluster coordination. When the StatefulSet pods reference `es-cluster-0.es-cluster`, `es-cluster-1.es-cluster`, etc., they're using DNS for discovery on that transport port, so I can reuse the same headless service rather than creating a new one.\n\nMy migration plan is to create the TLS certificates and secrets, set up a new ConfigMap with the ES 8.11.1 configuration, then replace the old StatefulSet with the new one. The existing `es-http` ClusterIP service will automatically route to the new pods since it selects `app: es-cluster`, and since it's just forwarding TCP traffic on port 9200, it'll work fine even though the new cluster uses HTTPS.\n\nFor the secrets, I need to generate a self-signed certificate covering the service DNS names (`es-http`, `es-http.elasticsearch`, `es-http.elasticsearch.svc`, `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`) and the pod discovery pattern (`*.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`), then create the `es-http-tls` secret with the cert, key, and CA, plus the `elastic-password` secret. - One certificate for HTTP TLS covering the `es-http` service names, and reuse it for transport TLS with `verification_mode: certificate` to skip hostname validation.\n\nNow I'm setting up the certificate generation process using OpenSSL to create a CA and server certificate...\n\nCreating Kubernetes secrets...\n\nI need to check whether the existing StatefulSet needs to be replaced or if I can update it in place.\n\nWhen I delete the old StatefulSet, the PVCs won't be automatically removed—they'll persist with data from ES 7.17.9. If I create a new StatefulSet with the same name, it'll try to reuse those existing PVCs, but the data format is incompatible between versions. I should delete both the StatefulSet and its PVCs before deploying the new version, or let the new StatefulSet create fresh volumes.\n\nFor the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` setting, it's needed for initial cluster bootstrapping in ES 8.x but can be removed once the cluster is healthy. I'll include it in the configuration for this clean deployment since it won't cause issues.\n\nThe oracle test will likely write and read back an index via HTTPS to `es-http:9200` using basic auth with the `elastic` user and password from the secret, so I need to ensure `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` is properly configured.\n\nFor the headless service and StatefulSet, I'll reuse the names from the old setup (`es-cluster`) so the pod DNS names follow the standard pattern, and I can reference the existing configuration structure.\n\nThe headless service exposes port 9300 for pod-to-pod discovery, which works fine for the new ES 8.11.1 pods, and the `es-http` service routes to port 9200 (now HTTPS) on the same pods—clients will just need to use HTTPS when connecting.\n\nNow I'm ready to implement the upgrade: I'll generate self-signed TLS certificates, create the necessary secrets for TLS and the elastic password, delete the old StatefulSet and its PVCs, update the ConfigMap with ES 8.11.1 settings including TLS configuration, and then deploy the new StatefulSet. Let me start writing this out. The elastic user password gets set via the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` environment variable. The `es-http` ClusterIP service handles client connections on port 9200, even though the headless service doesn't expose it. Before deploying the new StatefulSet, I need to delete the old PVCs from the ES 7.17.9 cluster so the new one can create fresh volumes. For the SSL verification, I need to decide between relaxing the hostname verification or generating a comprehensive certificate with all the pod SANs included. Since I know the pod hostnames ahead of time, I'll generate a cert with all the necessary SANs to avoid verification issues. Now I'll write a bash script to automate the entire setup process.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2514,"cache_read_input_tokens":37707,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2514},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0406e1a2-236f-48f3-a2b3-94bc9a85fba7","uuid":"d56427d8-cdde-4bc6-971f-0d46584ae06e","request_id":"req_011CceqrGE6E4w26K8Lh7uHm"}
